/-
  Data.PDF.Content.Encoding.PdfDoc — the PDFDocEncoding table

  Ports `Pdf.Content.Encoding.PdfDoc` from Hackage's `pdf-toolbox-content`
  (https://github.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox, `content/lib/Pdf/Content/Encoding/PdfDoc.hs`,
  fetched from
  `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox/master/content/lib/Pdf/Content/Encoding/PdfDoc.hs`),
  module 8 of the `pdf-toolbox-content` import documented in
  `docs/imports/PdfToolboxContent/dependencies.md`.

  PDF32000-1:2008 Annex D.3's PDFDocEncoding table, mapping single-byte codes
  0-255 to Unicode characters — except codes 127, 159, and 173, which
  upstream leaves undefined (absent from the table, matching the PDF spec's
  own "undefined" markers for those codes).

  ## Design

  Same representation choice as `Data.PDF.Content.Encoding.WinAnsi`:
  `Std.HashMap UInt8 Data.Text`, transcribed directly from upstream's
  `(code, "\xHHHH")` pair list rather than the `zip`-of-two-lists shape used
  by `WinAnsi`/`MacRoman`.

  Upstream's own table has a duplicate: both byte code 22 and byte code 23
  map to `"\x0017"` (verified against
  `content/lib/Pdf/Content/Encoding/PdfDoc.hs` lines 37-38 of the fetched
  source — this is not a copy/paste error introduced by this port). Per the
  scope note in `docs/imports/PdfToolboxContent/dependencies.md`, this
  apparent upstream typo is preserved byte-for-byte rather than "fixed": both
  entries are transcribed as-is below, and since they agree on the value
  there is no ambiguity for `Std.HashMap.ofList` to resolve either way.
-/
